===============================================================================
1. How to use
===============================================================================

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.1. Build the NetBSD distribution
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this procedure, NetBSD source tree is in /usr/src, NetBSD build-tools is in
/usr/tools, NetBSD compiled objects is in /usr/obj, NetBSD version is 7.1.2,
machine is amd64, and machine archtecture is x86_64.

How to build NetBSD source tree is here. Don't read if you understand or done
it.

First, download NetBSD source sets. Then extract it to /usr/src directory.

    # ftp ftp://ftp.netbsd.org/pub/NetBSD/NetBSD-7.1.2/source/
    ...
    ftp> mget .tgz
    ...
    ftp> bye
    # ls | grep 'tgz$' | xargs -n 1 -I % tar zxf -C /
    # ls | grep 'tgz$' | xargs rm

Second, build it using build.sh.

    # mkdir /usr/obj /usr/tools
    # cd /usr/src
    # ./build.sh -O ../obj -T ../tools -x -X ../xsrc tools
    # ./build.sh -O ../obj -T ../tools -x -X ../xsrc distribution

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.2. Install pkgtools/pkg_install
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

basepkg(1) is tested by latest pkgtools/pkg_install[1]. I recommend that
install it from pkgsrc(7).

How to get pkgsrc(7) is here. Don't read if you understand or done it.

    # ftp ftp://ftp.netbsd.org/pub/pkgsrc/stable/pkgsrc.tar.gz
    # tar zxf pkgsrc.tar.gz -C /usr
    # rm pkgsrc.tar.gz

Run make(1) with "install clean clean-depends" targets on pkgtools/pkg_install.

    # cd /usr/pkgsrc/pkgtools/pkg_install
    # make install clean clean-depends

Or we can use pkgin(1) instead of pkgsrc(7). pkgin is a binary package manager
for pkgsrc(7)[2].

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.3. Run basepkg.sh
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Run basepkg.sh(1) with pkg and kern option.

    # ./basepkg.sh pkg
    # ./basepkg.sh kern

Packages are created under the
packages/<release-version>/<machine>-<machine_arch> directory.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.4. How to install package
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Running pkg_add(1) with "-K var/db/basepkg" for separate database from
pkgsrc(7).

    # pkg_add -K /var/db/basepkg games-games-bin-7.1.tgz

But etc categorized packages are exception. They are installed to
/var/tmp/basepkg because the way keeps from overwrite existing files under the
/etc. If you want to update the configuration files, please run etcupdate(8)
manually.

    # etcupdate -s /var/tmp/basepkg

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.5. pkgsrc-wip
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

basepkg(1) is imported to pkgsrc-wip[3]. You can install basepkg to your system
using pkgsrc-wip. But it supporting only latest version package.

    # cd /usr/pkgsrc/wip/basepkg
    # make install clean clean-depends

basepkg.sh(1), README and others are installed to /usr/pkg/basepkg. You can run
basepkg.sh(1) on /usr/pkg/basepkg directory. Packages are placed in
/usr/pkg/basepkg/packages directory.

